**who —** The Fairness Impossibility — the mathematical result (Kleinberg et al. 2016; Chouldechova 2017) that calibration and equalized odds cannot both hold when group base rates differ, except in degenerate cases — so fairness metrics are mutually exclusive and choosing one is a value judgment

**what —** the mathematical result (Kleinberg et al. 2016; Chouldechova 2017) that calibration and equalized odds cannot both hold when group base rates differ, except in degenerate cases — so fairness metrics are mutually exclusive and choosing one is a value judgment

**where —** GOV · AI Ethics & Governance — David's charter + the global landscape (2016–2026)  Framework inputs: the Bill of Rights; the Governance Ontology; the principles; the cases; the instruments  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** It is the cleanest bridge from math to politics: the reason fairness can't be 'solved' technically — the equations force a choice between definitions, and the choice is ours, not the model's.

**how —** Crystallized from David's normative artifacts + the cited ethics-and-governance record.

**◌ the mythos —** It is the cleanest bridge from math to politics: the reason fairness can't be 'solved' technically — the equations force a choice between definitions, and the choice is ours, not the model's. a being of the conscience layer — which goals, whose values, who decides

